definition: "Troponin is a protein complex found in cardiac and skeletal muscle that regulates the interaction between actin and myosin during muscle contraction. Cardiac troponin I (cTnI) and cardiac troponin T (cTnT) are specific to the heart and are released into the bloodstream when cardiac muscle cells are damaged or under stress. High-sensitivity troponin assays (hs-cTnI and hs-cTnT) can detect cardiac troponin concentrations 10–100× lower than conventional troponin tests, enabling detection of subclinical myocardial injury — cardiac stress occurring at levels too low to cause symptoms or detectable electrocardiographic changes. In emergency medicine, high-sensitivity troponin transformed the diagnosis of acute MI; in longevity medicine, chronically detectable troponin in asymptomatic individuals is a powerful predictor of future cardiac events and mortality."
why_it_matters: "High-sensitivity troponin is unique among cardiovascular biomarkers in that it directly reflects current cardiac muscle stress — not just cardiovascular risk factors or structural markers, but actual myocardial damage occurring right now, at subclinical levels. In large population studies, chronically elevated hs-troponin — well below the thresholds used in emergency medicine to diagnose heart attack — is one of the strongest independent predictors of future cardiac events, heart failure, and all-cause mortality. The Dallas Heart Study and multiple other cohorts have found that hs-troponin in the upper quartile of detectable range among asymptomatic adults predicts a 3–5× higher risk of cardiovascular events over the following decade. It captures a form of cardiac stress that echocardiography, stress testing, and coronary calcium scoring do not directly measure — making it a genuinely complementary addition to comprehensive cardiovascular risk assessment."

